On the Reproducibility of the IPCC's climate sensitivity

Jacoby links to a blog page which explains the logarithmic relationship of CO2
concentrations and radiative forcing. Contrary to Jacoby's implication, this is
actually a well accepted part of climate science. For instance, see [Myhre et al
1998](http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/98GL01908/epdf) (table 3), who
give detailed estimates of this logarithmic relationship.

However, as CO2 concentrations rise, the fraction of CO2 which remains in the
atmosphere (rather than being absorbed by the ocean) is projected to increase
(see [Jones et al
2013](http://nldr.library.ucar.edu/repository/assets/osgc/OSGC-000-000-019-143.pdf)).
The net effect is that the relationship between total CO2 emissions and surface
temperature is almost linear. See the figure below from the [IPCC AR5 WG1 Summary
for Policymakers](http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar5/wg1/WG1AR5_SPM_FINAL.pdf).
